===Adverb===
{{en-adv|-}}

# {{lb|en|formal}} From [[there]], from that place or from that time.
#: {{ux|en|I came '''thence'''.}}
#: {{ux|en|Cross fix at 6000 feet, '''thence''' descend to 3000 feet and fly direct to MAP (missed approach point).}}
#* {{RQ:Shakespeare Tempest|I|ii|page=2}}
#*: {{smallcaps|Miranda}}: O the heauens, / What fowle play had we, that we came from '''thence'''? / Or bleſſed was't we did?
#*: {{smallcaps|Prospero}}: Both, both my Girle. / By fowle-play (as thou ſayſt) were we heau'd '''thence''', / But bleſſedly holpe hither.
#* '''2005''', Alpha Chiang and Kevin Wainwright, ''Fundamental Methods of Mathematical Economics'' (4th ed.), McGraw-Hill International, p. 605
#*: From this we can find the characteristic roots <math>b_1</math> and <math>b_2</math> and '''thence''' proceed to the remaining steps of the solution process.
# {{lb|en|literary}} Deriving from this [[fact]] or [[circumstance]]; [[therefore]], [[therefrom]].
# {{lb|en|archaic}} From that [[time]]; [[thenceforth]]; [[thereafter]]

